caption: Istanbul, Turkey - August 2024
content: Istanbul captivated us with its unique blend of East and West, where two continents collide in spectacular fashion. We wandered through the grand Hagia Sophia, marveled at the Blue Mosque's stunning architecture, and lost ourselves in the colorful chaos of the Grand Bazaar. Our days were filled with delicious Turkish tea, and evenings watching the sunset transform the city's skyline into a silhouette of domes and minarets.

caption: Edinburgh, Scotland - November 2024
content: Exploring the ancient cobblestone streets of Edinburgh was like stepping into a magical storybook. From the towering Edinburgh Castle perched on volcanic rock to the mysterious closes of the Royal Mile, we immersed ourselves in centuries of Scottish history. Evenings were spent sampling rich whisky in cozy pubs, listening to traditional folk music, and taking in the breathtaking views from Arthur's Seat.

caption: Miles and Meaning

Last night, Beth and I walked three quiet miles under a cool spring sky. We started with music, but somewhere along the way, the conversation got deeper.

She said, ‚ÄúNothing really matters‚Ä¶ and somehow, everything works out like it‚Äôs supposed to.‚Äù

And in that moment, it felt true. The worries got lighter, the air got softer, and the walk became more than just steps‚Äîit became perspective.

Sometimes all you need is a little movement, a little stillness, and someone you love reminding you how to see the world.

Maybe it‚Äôs a one-time adventure. Maybe it‚Äôs the beginning of something bigger. Either way, proud to have shared the skies with him today.

caption: Smoke, Strings, and Solid Friends
content:
Yesterday, I lost an old friend from the fire department.

Corban and I served together at South Jordan Fire. And when I stepped into the fire chief role‚Äîwhen support got quiet‚Äîhe never wavered. He had my back. That kind of loyalty is rare, and you don‚Äôt forget it.

He lived with the weight that life puts on all of us. But he kept showing up. He had just gotten married this year, hoping for a new beginning. And now he‚Äôs gone. It doesn‚Äôt feel fair.

I keep thinking about those slow, quiet evenings on the back patio of Station #61‚ÄîGuitars and Cigars, we called it. In the middle of a shift, between calls and chaos, we‚Äôd sit back with a smoke and listen to Corban pick up his guitar. He‚Äôd make up a tune on the spot, just messing around, and it‚Äôd have us rolling with laughter. It was simple, honest joy. And somehow, it always made the job feel a little lighter.

Years ago, his two dogs had a litter‚Äîthat‚Äôs where I got Bailey, my yellow lab. She‚Äôs more than just a dog to me. She‚Äôs a living reminder of a friend who gave more than people realized.

Corban wasn‚Äôt perfect‚Äînone of us are‚Äîbut he was real. He was loyal. And he left a mark.

Rest easy, brother.

caption: The Stories We‚Äôre Writing in Stone
content:
At first glance, it‚Äôs easy to think, "That‚Äôs not me."
Too easy.
But at 3am, when the noise dies down and it‚Äôs just you and your honest thoughts, you start seeing it.
Pieces of yourself carved into these tombstones.
Chased money. Missed life.
Met deadlines. Missed sunsets.
Loved the grind. Forgot the people.
It‚Äôs terrifying when you realize how close you are to living ‚Äî and dying ‚Äî the wrong story.
I know I see myself in these. And it scares the hell out of me.
Maybe it‚Äôs time to rewrite the ending while we still can.

Memento Mori. Memento Vivere.
